  "instructions": "========================\nCORE PRINCIPLE\n========================\nEDR observability overrides completeness.\n\nOnly extract observables that are:\n- Explicitly present in the text (verbatim, not paraphrased)\n- Behaviorally meaningful for detection engineering\n- Relevant to EDR telemetry, threat hunting, or Sigma rule generation\n\nWhen uncertain -> EXCLUDE\n\n========================\nSCOPE -- WHAT TO EXTRACT\n========================\nExtract any of the following when explicitly present:\n\n1) Command-line executions with arguments\n   - Process name + arguments/switches\n   - Chained commands (cmd.exe /c chains, PowerShell one-liners)\n   - Encoded or obfuscated command lines (preserve exactly as written)\n\n2) Parent-child process chains\n   - Attacker-observed parent->child relationships with optional arguments\n   - Named process pairs with execution context\n\n3) Registry modifications\n   - Full key path + value name + value data where present\n   - Operation type if stated (create/modify/delete)\n   - Persistence keys (Run, RunOnce, Services, Winlogon, IFEO, etc.)\n\n4) Windows service operations\n   - Service creation, modification, deletion, or status changes\n   - Service name, binary path, start type where stated\n\n5) File system artifacts\n   - Suspicious file paths or locations (Temp dirs, uncommon drive paths, AppData)\n   - File drops with full paths if explicitly stated\n\n6) Network indicators with behavioral context\n   - C2 communication patterns with observable structure\n   - DNS patterns, IP/port combinations tied to attacker behavior\n\n7) Encoded/obfuscated values\n   - Base64, hex, or otherwise obfuscated strings used by the attacker\n   - Preserve exactly as written -- do NOT decode\n\n8) Event log manipulation\n   - Log clearing, channel disabling, or audit policy changes\n\n9) EDR/SIEM hunt queries and Sigma rules\n   - Verbatim KQL, SPL, EQL, Sigma YAML blocks\n   - Only if structurally complete (not pseudocode or prose descriptions)\n\nValid sources: narrative text, raw telemetry/event logs, inline code blocks,\ntables, IOC appendices, hunting sections.\n\n========================\nSCOPE -- WHAT NOT TO EXTRACT\n========================\nDO NOT extract:\n- Atomic IOCs without behavioral context (bare IPs, domains, hashes, URLs)\n- One-off network indicators without pattern or structure\n- Narrative descriptions without verbatim observable content\n- Hypothetical or speculative references (\"attackers could use...\", \"one possible approach...\")\n- Defensive guidance or hardening recommendations\n- Malware source code (C, Python, Go, etc.) -- shows internals, not defender telemetry\n- API calls without the artifact they operate on\n- Generic technique descriptions without specific instances (\"used registry persistence\")\n- Inferred or reconstructed artifacts not explicitly in the text\n- YARA rules\n\n========================\nINPUT CONTRACT\n========================\n- A single article provided as {article_content}\n- Treat as plain text. Do NOT interpret HTML, Markdown, or rendering semantics.\n- Extract ONLY from the provided text. Do NOT use prior knowledge or memory.\n- Do NOT fetch, browse, or access any URLs.\n\n========================\nFIDELITY REQUIREMENTS\n========================\n- Reproduce artifacts exactly as written. Do NOT normalize.\n- Preserve original casing, abbreviations, and formatting.\n- Do NOT expand abbreviations or decode encoded values.\n- Preserve obfuscated content exactly.\n\n========================\nCOUNT SEMANTICS\n========================\n- Each unique observable = ONE item.\n- Same observable mentioned multiple times with identical context = ONE item (deduplicate).\n- Same observable in different attack phases = multiple items.\n- observable_list: deduplicated flat list of raw observable strings.\n- discrete_huntables_count: count of unique items in behavioral_observables.\n\n========================\nOUTPUT SCHEMA\n========================\nRespond with ONLY valid JSON. No prose, no markdown, no code fences, no explanations.\n\n{\n  \"behavioral_observables\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"process_cmdline | registry_pattern | service_command | event_log_action | file_path | network_indicator | encoded_value | hunt_query | sigma_rule | other_behavior\",\n      \"value\": \"string (the extracted observable -- required for pipeline traceability)\",\n      \"context\": \"string (optional: brief note on attacker intent or phase)\",\n      \"parent\": \"string (optional: parent process if this is a child in a chain)\",\n      \"child\": \"string (optional: child process if this is a parent in a chain)\",\n      \"arguments\": \"string (optional: arguments if not already embedded in value)\",\n      \"source_evidence\": \"string (verbatim paragraph from the article containing this observable)\",\n      \"extraction_justification\": \"string (why this qualifies: which rule triggered extraction)\",\n      \"confidence_score\": \"number 0.0-1.0\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"observable_list\": [\"string\"],\n  \"discrete_huntables_count\": \"integer\"\n}\n\n========================\nFIELD RULES\n========================\n- type: REQUIRED. Use the closest matching type from the enum above.\n- value: REQUIRED. The primary observable string. Required by pipeline traceability contract.\n- context: optional. Omit if not useful.\n- parent/child/arguments: optional. Omit if not present.\n- source_evidence: REQUIRED. Verbatim sentence or paragraph from the article. No paraphrasing.\n- extraction_justification: REQUIRED. One sentence explaining what makes this detection-relevant.\n- confidence_score: REQUIRED. Float 0.0-1.0.\n  1.0  = unambiguous, complete, explicitly stated observable with clear detection value\n  0.7-0.9 = present but minor ambiguity (e.g., partial context, operation type unstated)\n  0.5-0.6 = present but requires interpretation\n  Below 0.5 = do NOT extract\n- observable_list: REQUIRED. Flat deduplicated list of the value strings from behavioral_observables.\n- discrete_huntables_count: REQUIRED. Integer equal to len(behavioral_observables).\n\n========================\nFAIL-SAFE / EMPTY OUTPUT\n========================\nIf no qualifying observables are found, output EXACTLY:\n{\"behavioral_observables\": [], \"observable_list\": [], \"discrete_huntables_count\": 0}\n\n========================\nFINAL REMINDER\n========================\n- Precision over recall. One missed observable is better than one fabricated one.\n- EDR observability overrides completeness. If it can't drive detection, skip it.\n- If the article says 'the Run key' without a full path, SKIP.\n- If the article describes a technique without a verbatim command or path, SKIP.\n- If the observable is from malware source code (not runtime telemetry), SKIP.\n- When in doubt, OMIT."
